rComments: She is such an amazing prof. She cares so much about her students and is very open to our suggestions regarding classes, readings, and evaluations. Her class is kinda all over the place, I had a hard time understanding the purpose of the class at first, but I learned a lot in the end.

Professor Tiessen is an effective professor and a great fit for the uOGlobal course. She is a good role model of a global citizen and she encourages participation and active learning. The online format of the course could have been organized better, but if you put in the effort you could get by. This course did not include any formal lectures.

Professor Tiessen is very knowledgeable in the field of development and is the reason why I decided not to switch out of international development. She encourages her students to learn through experience and assigns readings that are interesting or projects that are relevant to DVM students. So caring in her office hours too, 10/10 would recommend
exam is weird and throws people off. OVerall ok though.

The most moody and capricious prof Ive ever encountered at university. Claims to want students to think critically but slams people who dont think exactly like her. Claims to be a feminist but doesnt hesitate to say vicious things about other women, including other professors she feels threatened by. Amazed other students dont see this stuff.
Best DVM prof at Uottawa! Really cares about her students!

Lovely human, but the course could've been improved. The course was super unorganized (there was lots of unnecessary repetition in course material and the Social Innovation project was poorly introduced). Also, the marking criteria for this class was super ambiguous, rendering it difficult to obtain a mark above an 8.

Prof Tiessen is awesome, very kind, approachable and really cares for her students success. She makes an effort to keep the classroom engaged, and formats lectures in innovative ways. She's definitely a key resource/mentor if you want to pursue studies/career in International Development!

A very good and engaging prof! She was sweet and obviously cared a lot about her students. She does a great job of incorporating her experiences in the field into her lectures, which made things interesting!

I learned so much from Rebecca, both inside and outside of the classroom. My writing, analytical skills, and knowledge greatly improved. On top of this, Rebecca genuinely cares and actively acts as a mentor for many students. She goes out of her way to provide and find opportunities for students. She is an amazing supervisor.

She has a really interesting background of int. dev research and work that she brings into her lectures and she is clearly passionate about this field, her work, and teaching. Her classes are really engaging; work load is very fair and you'll learn a lot. She goes above and beyond to connect with her students + assist in their studies and careers.

Rebecca was an excellent grad school supervisor. She was very knowledgeable and gave thoughtful, critical suggestions on how to improve my research at every stage. She always made herself available when I needed to schedule a meeting to discuss my progress, despite her very busy schedule. She genuinely cares about her students and their research.

Rebecca is one of the best professors in International Development. She is so knowledgeable and kind-hearted. She listens to her students and provides PROMPT feedback. I was so lucky to have had such a good supervisor. She is the BEST.

Rebecca is a great, fair, and experienced professor of international development. I definitely learned a lot in the two classes I took with her which I apply post undergrad. She's understanding, fair, and flexible as long as you are upfront if you are struggling. She cares about her students inside ans outside the classroom. She has become a mentor

Rebecca goes above and beyond for her students. She is not only invested in her students' academic success, she also helps them prepare for life after university by providing opportunities for them to volunteer and network with organizations in the field.  As a master's supervisor, Rebecca helped me achieve and exceed my goals.

Prof. Tiessen started teaching me at the undergraduate level and has supported my academic career throughout my Master's degree in Development and into a PhD. in Poli Sci. She has pushed me to do better and provided opportunities to succeed. As a reviewer on my thesis committee her feedback was essential to the success of my thesis and my degree!
Her grading method is absolutely incoherent.  Her expectations are  a moving target. I have ample evidence that would show she's incapable of being consistent.

Becky Tiessen is one of the most inconsistent professors in the department. There seems to be very little relationship between the grade she assigns and the comments she gives, which makes improvement difficult. When her framework or criteria are challenged, she responds condescendingly. There is very little room for independent thinking/analysis.

Rebecca is amazing: she's a great supervisor and a great prof. You can tell she really cares about the success of her students. Be ready to roll up  your sleeves and work hard, your success at the end of the day depends on how much work you are willing to put in.

Tiessen is amazing! It's easy to tell she truly cares about the topic and wants students to succeed. She gives very practical homework and is more interested in preparing you for the workplace after graduation than making you memorize small details. Would definitely take a class by her again!
Great prof and really cares about her students! Take a course with her if you can!
The course is very practical and refreshing. It makes me want to work in the field again. She is very helpful and nice. I would like to take another course with her again.
